d Koninkrijk","Wyke, Devon, England":"Wyke, Devon, England","Wreyland Manor, Lustleigh, Teignbridge district, Devonshire, England":"Lustleigh, Devon, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Devon, England":"Devon, England"},"en":{"1170–1248":"1170–1248","1155–Male":"1155–Deceased","1157–Male":"1157–Deceased","1161–Male":"1161–Deceased","1164–Male":"1164–Deceased","1167–Male":"1167–Deceased","1178–Female":"1178–Deceased","1210–1248":"1210–1248","1213–1248":"1213–1248","1132–1195":"1132–1195","1134–Female":"1134–Deceased","1132":"1132","1164":"1164","1195":"1195","1161":"1161","1170":"1170","1248":"1248","1213":"1213","1157":"1157","1134":"1134","1178":"1178","1167":"1167","1210":"1210","1155":"1155","about 1200":"about 1200","about 1154":"about 1154","about 1210":"about 1210","North Wyke, South Tawton, Devon, England":"South Tawton, Devon, England, United Kingdom","Wyke, Devon, England":"Wyke, Devon, England","Wreyland Manor, Lustleigh, Teignbridge district, Devonshire, England":"Lustleigh, Devon, England, United Kingdom","Devon, England":"Devon, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Wrey","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["1  English: locative name from Wray Barton (Devon).","2  English: nickname, perhaps ‘the twisted, crooked one’, from Middle English  <i>wry(e)</i> ‘awry’, a derivative of Old English  <i>wrīgian</i> ‘to turn’. It is possible, however, that  <i>le Wrey</i> (1313) is a scribal error for  <i>de Wrey</i>, and that the following early bearers belong under (1).","3  N English:  see  Wray  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Wray","meanings":["English (northern):","from Middle English <i>wra</i> (Old Norse <i>vrá</i>) ‘nook, corner of land’, a topographic name for someone who lived at or by a nook, corner of land, or isolated place, or a habitational name from a place so named, such as Wray in Tunstall (Lancashire), Wrea in Kirkham (Lancashire), and High and Low Wreah in Hensingham (Cumberland). The name was taken to Ulster by a Yorkshire family in the reign of Elizabeth I, and was used interchangeably in the counties of Derry and Donegal with <i>Raw</i>, <i>Ray</i>, <i>Rea</i>, and occasionally   McRae  .","common post-medieval spelling of   Ray  ,   Rae  , or   Ree  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["‘Attainment’."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William de Wrey was born in 1170, in South Tawton, Devon, England, United Kingdom, his father, Robert de Wrey, was 38 and his mother, Sybil Abbott, was 37. He married Alice Kelley about 1200, in Wyke, Devon, England. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He died in 1248, in Lustleigh, Devon, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 78."},"et":{"1170–1248":"1170–1248","1155–Male":"1155–Surnud","1157–Male":"1157–Surnud","1161–Male":"1161–Surnud","1164–Male":"1164–Surnud","1167–Male":"1167–Surnud","1178–Female":"1178–Surnud","1210–1248":"1210–1248","1213–1248":"1213–1248","1132–1195":"1132–1195","1134–Female":"1134–Surnud","1132":"1132","1164":"1164","1195":"1195","1161":"1161","1170":"1170","1248":"1248","1213":"1213","1157":"1157